{{Human history}}
The '''history of the world''' (or '''world history''') describes the '''history of humanity''' (or '''human history''') as determined by the study of [[Archaeology|archaeological]] and [[Recorded history|written records]], beginning with the [[Inventions of writing|invention of writing]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia Americana|last=Diringer|first=David|publisher=|year=|isbn=|edition=1986|volume=29|location=|pages=558|chapter=Writing|quote=Writing gives permanence to men's knowledge and enables them to communicate over great distances.... The complex society of a higher civilization would be impossible without the art of writing.|via=}}</ref><ref name="WebsterWH">{{cite book|last1=Webster|first1=Hutton|title=World History|date=1921|publisher=D. C. Heath|location=Boston|page=27|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cboXAAAAIAAJ&pg=PR5&pg=PA27}}</ref>

The [[Cradle of civilization|roots of civilization]] reach back to the earliest introduction of primitive technology and culture, while [[Prehistory]] begins in the [[Paleolithic|Palaeolithic Era]], or "Early Stone Age", which is followed by the [[Neolithic|Neolithic Era]], or "New Stone Age", and the [[Neolithic Revolution|Agricultural Revolution]] (between 8000 and 5000 [[BCE]]) in the [[Fertile Crescent]]. The latter period marked a change in human history, as humans began the systematic [[Agriculture|husbandry]] of plants and animals.<ref name="Tudge">{{cite book | last = Tudge | first = Colin | authorlink = Colin Tudge f| title = [[Neanderthals, Bandits and Farmers|Neanderthals, Bandits and Farmers: How Agriculture Really Began]] | date = 1998 | publisher = Weidenfeld & Nicolson | location = London | isbn = 0-297-84258-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Bellwood|first1=Peter|title=First Farmers: the origins of agricultural societies|date=2005|publisher=Blackwell|location=Malden, MA|isbn=0-631-20566-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Cohen|first1=Mark Nathan|title=The food crisis in prehistory overpopulation and the origins of agriculture|date=1977|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven|isbn=0-300-02016-3}}</ref> Agriculture advanced, and most humans transitioned from a [[nomad]]ic to a settled lifestyle as farmers in [[civilization|permanent settlements]]. Nomadism continued in some locations, especially in isolated regions with few domesticable plant species,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Diamond|first1=Jared|authorlink1=Jared Diamond|title=[[Guns, Germs, and Steel]]: the fates of human societies|date=1997|publisher=Cape|location=London|isbn=0224038095}}</ref> but the relative security and increased productivity provided by farming allowed human communities to expand into increasingly larger units, fostered by advances in [[history of transport|transportation]].

As farming developed, [[Cereal|grain agriculture]] became more sophisticated and prompted a [[division of labour]] to store food between growing seasons. Labour divisions then led to the rise of a leisured [[upper class]] and the development of [[City|cities]]. The growing complexity of human societies necessitated systems of [[writing]] and [[accounting]].<ref name="DSB-AO">{{cite journal | author=Schmandt-Besserat, Denise| authorlink=Denise Schmandt-Besserat| title=Signs of Life| journal=Archaeology Odyssey| date=January–February 2002| url=https://webspace.utexas.edu/dsbay/Docs/SignsofLife.pdf| pages=6–7, 63}}</ref> Many cities developed on the [[Bank (geography)|banks]] of lakes and rivers as early as 3000 BCE, when some of the first prominent, well-developed settlements had arisen in [[Mesopotamia]] ("the Land between the Rivers"),<ref name="McNeill-Sumer">{{cite book | last = McNeill | first = William H. | authorlink = William H. McNeill (historian) | title = A World History | origyear = 1967 | edition = 4th | date = 1999 | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | location = New York | isbn = 0-19-511615-1 | page = 15 | chapter = In The Beginning}}</ref> on the banks of [[ancient Egypt|Egypt]]'s [[Nile|Nile River]],<ref>{{cite book|author1=[[John Baines (Egyptologist)|Baines, John]] |author2=Jaromir Malek|title=The Cultural Atlas of Ancient Egypt|edition=revised|publisher=Facts on File|date=2000|isbn=0-8160-4036-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Bard | first = KA | title = Encyclopedia of the Archaeology of Ancient Egypt | publisher = Routledge | location = NY, NY | date = 1999|isbn=0-415-18589-0}}</ref><ref name="grimal1992">{{cite book|first=Nicolas|last=Grimal|title=A History of Ancient Egypt|publisher=Blackwell Books|date=1992|isbn=0-631-19396-0}}</ref> in the [[Indus Valley Civilisation|Indus River valley]]<ref>{{cite book |editor=Allchin, Raymond |editor-link=Raymond Allchin |date=1995 |title=The Archaeology of Early Historic South Asia: The Emergence of Cities and States |location=New York |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=D. K. |last=Chakrabarti |date=2004 |title=Indus Civilization Sites in India: New Discoveries |publisher=Marg Publications |location=Mumbai |isbn=81-85026-63-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor-link=Ahmad Hasan Dani |editor-last=Dani |editor-first=Ahmad Hasan |editor2-last=Mohen |editor2-first=J-P. |date=1996 |title=History of Humanity, Volume III, From the Third Millennium to the Seventh Century BC |location=New York/Paris |publisher=Routledge/UNESCO |isbn=0-415-09306-6}}</ref> and along the [[Yellow River|major rivers]] of [[China]].<ref name="National Gallery of Art">{{cite web|url=http://www.nga.gov/content/ngaweb/exhibitions/1999/chinese_archaeology.html|title=The Golden Age of Chinese Archaeology: Celebrated Discoveries from The People's Republic of China|last=|first=|date=|publisher=National Gallery of Art|location=|work=|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www-chaos.umd.edu/history/ancient1.html|title=The Ancient Dynasties|publisher=University of Maryland|accessdate=12 January 2008}}</ref><ref name="Lee">{{cite journal|last1=Lee|first1=Yun Kuen|title=Building the Chronology of Early Chinese History|journal=Asian Perspectives|date=2002|volume=41|issue=1|pages=15–42|url=http://hdl.handle.net/10125/17161|issn=1535-8283|doi=10.1353/asi.2002.0006}}</ref>

The history of the [[Old World]] (particularly Europe and the Mediterranean) is commonly divided into [[ancient history]] (or "Antiquity"), up to 476 CE; [[post-classical history]] (or "the [[Middle Ages]]"),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/|title=Internet Medieval Sourcebook Project|last=Halsall|first=Paul|date=January 26, 1996|website=Internet History Sourcebooks Project|publisher=Fordham University|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-orb.net/ |title=The Online Reference Book of Medieval Studies |last= |first= |date= |website= |publisher=ORB |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414091545/http://www.the-orb.net/ |archive-date=14 April 2009 |dead-url=yes |accessdate=18 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> from the 5th through 15th centuries, including the rise of Christianity, the [[Islamic Golden Age]] (c. 750 CE&nbsp;– c. 1258 CE) and the early Italian [[Renaissance]] (beginning around 1300 CE);<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burckhardt|first1=Jacob|authorlink=Jacob Burckhardt|translator-first=S. G. C.|translator-last=Middlemore|title=The Civilization of the Renaissance in Italy|date=1878|publisher=George Allen & Unwin|location=London|url=http://www.boisestate.edu/courses/hy309/docs/burckhardt/burckhardt.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080921145058/http://www.boisestate.edu/courses/hy309/docs/burckhardt/burckhardt.html|archivedate=21 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor-first=Adolphus W.|editor-last=Ward|url=http://www.uni-mannheim.de/mateo/camenaref/cmh/cmh.html |title=The Cambridge Modern History. Vol 1: The Renaissance|date=1902|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref> the [[early modern period]],<ref name="rice1970">{{cite book|last=Rice|first=Eugene, F., Jr.|title=The Foundations of Early Modern Europe: 1460–1559|date=1970|publisher=W.W. Norton & Co.|authorlink=Eugene F. Rice, Jr.}}</ref> from the 15th century to the late 18th, including the [[Age of Enlightenment]]; and the [[Modern history#Western transformations|late modern period]], from the [[Industrial Revolution]] to the present, including [[contemporary history]].

In the mid-15th century, the invention of modern [[printing]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.open2.net/historyandthearts/discover_science/gberg_synopsis.html |title=What Did Gutenberg Invent? |last= |first= |date= |website= |publisher=BBC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506073655/http://www.open2.net/historyandthearts/discover_science/gberg_synopsis.html |archive-date=6 May 2008 |dead-url=yes |accessdate=20 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> employing [[movable type]], revolutionized [[communication]], helping end the Middle Ages and ushering in the [[Scientific Revolution]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Grant|first1=Edward|title=The Foundations of Modern Science in the Middle Ages: their religious, institutional, and intellectual contexts|date=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521567626}}</ref> By the 18th century, the accumulation of [[knowledge]] and [[technology]], especially in Europe, had reached a [[Critical mass (sociodynamics)|critical mass]] that brought about the Industrial Revolution.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Understanding the Industrial Revolution|last=More|first=Charles|publisher=|year=2000|isbn=|location=|pages=|quote=|via=Questia}}</ref> Outside the Old World, including [[ancient China]] and [[History of India|ancient India]], historical timelines unfolded differently. However, by the 18th century, due to extensive [[International trade|world trade]] and [[colonization]], the histories of most civilizations had become substantially intertwined (see [[Globalization]]). In the last quarter-millennium, the rates of growth of population, knowledge, technology, communications, commerce, weapons destructiveness and environmental degradation have greatly accelerated, creating opportunities and perils that now confront the planet's human communities.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Biba|first1=Erin|title=Meet the Co-Founder of an Apocalypse Think Tank|journal=Scientific American|date=1 June 2015|volume=312|issue=6|page=26|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/meet-the-co-founder-of-an-apocalypse-think-tank/|quote=Throughout history our ancestors have confronted risks: pestilence, storms, earthquakes and human-induced disasters. But this century is different. It's the first when one species, ours, can determine the planet's future, threaten our civilization and jeopardize the existence of future generations.|doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0615-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nordhaus|first1=William D.|authorlink1=William Nordhaus|title=A New Solution: the Climate Club|journal=The New York Review of Books|date=4 June 2015|volume=LXII|issue=10|pages=36–39|quote=Climate change has become the premier environmental problem facing the globe.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Baten, Jörg |title=A History of the Global Economy. From 1500 to the Present.|date=2016|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=1–13|isbn=9781107507180}}</ref>
