==Prehistory==
{{Main article|Prehistory|Human evolution}}

===Early humans===
[[File:Lascaux 04.jpg|thumb|Cave painting, [[Lascaux|Lascaux, France]]]]
[[Molecular clock|Genetic]] measurements indicate that the ape lineage which would lead to ''Homo sapiens'' diverged from the lineage that would lead to chimpanzees (the closest living relative of modern humans) around six million years ago.<ref name=ChenLi>{{cite journal |last1=Chen|first1=F.C.|last2=Li|first2=W.H. | date = 2001 | title = Genomic divergences between humans and other hominoids and the effective population size of the common ancestor of humans and chimpanzees | journal = Am J Hum Genet | volume = 68 | issue = 2 | pages = 444–456 | doi = 10.1086/318206 | pmid = 11170892 | pmc = 1235277}}</ref> It is thought that the [[Australopithecine]] genus, which were likely the first apes to walk upright, eventually gave rise to genus ''Homo''. [[Anatomically modern human]]s arose in Africa about 200,000 years ago, and reached [[behavioral modernity|behavioural modernity]] about 50,000 years ago.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnh.si.edu/anthro/humanorigins/ha/sap.htm |title=Human Ancestors Hall: Homo Sapiens |work=Human Origins Initiative |publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]] |accessdate=30 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071015030431/http://www.mnh.si.edu/anthro/humanorigins/ha/sap.htm |archivedate=15 October 2007 }}</ref>

Modern humans [[Recent African origin of modern humans|spread]] rapidly from [[Africa]] into the frost-free zones of [[Europe]] and [[Asia]] around 60,000 years ago.<ref name="Stringer2012">{{Cite journal | last1 = Stringer | first1 = C. | title = AOP | doi = 10.1038/485033a | journal = Nature | volume = 485 | issue = 7396 | pages = 33–35 | year = 2012 | pmid = 22552077 | pmc = }}</ref> The rapid expansion of humankind to [[North America]] and [[Oceania]] took place at the climax of the [[Last glacial period|most recent]] [[ice age]], when temperate regions of today were extremely inhospitable. Yet, humans had colonized nearly all the ice-free parts of the globe by the end of the Ice Age, some 12,000 years ago. Other [[Hominidae|hominids]] such as ''[[Homo erectus]]'' had been using simple wood and stone tools for [[Millennium|millennia]], but as time progressed, tools became far more refined and complex. At some point, humans [[Control of fire by early humans|began using fire]] for [[heat]] and [[cooking]]. They also [[Origin of language|developed language]] in the [[Paleolithic|Palaeolithic]] period and a conceptual repertoire that included systematic burial of the dead and adornment of the living. Early artistic expression can be found in the form of [[cave painting]]s and [[sculpture]]s made from wood and bone, showing a spirituality generally interpreted as [[animism]], or even [[shamanism]]. During this period, all humans lived as [[hunter-gatherer]]s, and were generally [[nomad]]ic.<ref>{{cite news|first=Hillary|last=Mayell|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2003/02/0220_030220_humanorigins2_2.html|title=When Did "Modern" Behavior Emerge in Humans?|date=20 February 2003|work=National Geographic}}</ref> Archaeological and genetic data suggest that the source populations of Palaeolithic hunter-gatherers survived in sparsely wooded areas and dispersed through areas of high [[primary productivity]] while avoiding dense forest cover.<ref name=Gavashelishvili23>{{cite journal |last1=Gavashelishvili|first1=A.|last2=Tarkhnishvili|first2=D. |year=2016 |title= Biomes and human distribution during the last ice age |journal= Global Ecology and Biogeography |doi=10.1111/geb.12437 |volume=25 |issue=5|pages=563–574}}</ref>

===Rise of civilization===
[[File:Sumerian 26th c Adab.jpg|thumb|[[Cuneiform script|Cuneiform]], the earliest known writing system]]
The [[Neolithic Revolution]], beginning about 8,000 BCE, saw the development of agriculture, which drastically changed the human lifestyle. [[Mesopotamia]] is the site of the earliest developments of the Neolithic Revolution. It has been identified as having "inspired some of the most important developments in human history including the invention of the [[wheel]], the planting of the first cereal [[crop]]s and the development of [[cursive]] script, [[Mathematics]], [[Astronomy]] and [[Agriculture]]."<ref name="historyandpolicy">{{cite web|url=http://www.historyandpolicy.org/papers/policy-paper-13.html|title=Iraq, past, present and future: a thoroughly-modern mandate?|last=Milton-Edwards|first=Beverley|date=May 2003|work=History & Policy|accessdate=9 December 2010}}</ref>

Farming permitted far denser populations, which in time organized into [[State (polity)|states]]. Agriculture also created [[food]] surpluses that could support people not directly engaged in food production. The development of agriculture permitted the creation of the first [[city|cities]]. These were centres of [[trade]], [[manufacturing]] and [[political power]] with nearly no agricultural production of their own. Cities established a [[symbiosis]] with their surrounding [[Rural area|countryside]]s, absorbing agricultural products and providing, in return, manufactured goods and varying degrees of military control and protection.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Stearns | first1 = Peter N. | authorlink1 = Peter Stearns |first2=William L. | last2= Langer | title = [[Encyclopedia of World History|The Encyclopedia of World History: Ancient, Medieval, and Modern, Chronologically Arranged]] | publisher = [[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|Houghton Mifflin Company]] | date = 24 September 2001 | isbn = 0-395-65237-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Chandler|first1=Tertius|title=Four thousand years of urban growth: an historical census|date=1987|publisher=St. David's University Press|location=Lewiston, NY|isbn=9780889462076}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Modelski|first1=George|authorlink1=George Modelski|title=World cities: -3000 to 2000|date=2003|publisher=Faros 2000|location=Washington, DC|isbn=9780967623016}}</ref>

The development of cities was synonymous with the rise of [[civilization]].<ref>The very word "[[civilization]]" comes from the [[Latin]] ''civilis'', meaning "civil," related to ''civis'', meaning "citizen," and ''civitas'', meaning "city" or "city-state."</ref> [[Cradle of civilization|Early civilizations]] arose first in Lower Mesopotamia (3500 BCE),<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ascalone|first1=Enrico|title=Mesopotamia: Assyrians, Sumerians, Babylonians (Dictionaries of Civilizations; 1)|date=2007|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=0520252667}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Lloyd|first1=Seton|title=The archaeology of Mesopotamia : from the Old Stone Age to the Persian conquest|date=1984|publisher=Thames and Hudson|location=New York|isbn=0500790094}}</ref> followed by [[Ancient Egypt|Egyptian civilization]] along the [[Nile]] (3000 BCE),<ref name="grimal1992"/> the [[Indus Valley Civilisation|Harappan civilization]] in the [[Indus River|Indus Valley]] (in present-day [[India]] and [[Pakistan]]; 2500 BCE)<ref>{{cite book|last1=Allchin|first1=Bridget|authorlink1=Bridget Allchin|last2=Allchin|first2=Raymond|authorlink2=Raymond Allchin|title=Origins of a civilization: the prehistory and early archaeology of South Asia|date=1997|publisher=Viking|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-0670877133}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Allchin|first1=Raymond|title=The archaeology of early historic South Asia : the emergence of cities and states|date=1995|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521376952}}</ref> and [[Ancient China|Chinese civilization]] in the [[Yellow River]] and [[Yangtze|Yangtze river]] (2200 BCE).<ref name="National Gallery of Art"/><ref name="Lee"/> These societies developed a number of unifying characteristics, including a central government, a complex economy and social structure, sophisticated language and writing systems, and distinct cultures and religions. [[Writing]] was another pivotal development in human history, as it made the administration of cities and expression of ideas far easier.

As complex civilizations arose, so did complex [[religion]]s, and the first of their kind apparently originated during this period.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zhu|first1=Tianshu|editor1-last=Compareti|editor1-first=Matteo|editor2-last=Raffetta|editor2-first=Paola|editor3-last=Scarcia|editor3-first=Gianroberto|title=Ērān ud Anērān: studies presented to Boris Ilich Maršak on the occasion of his 70th birthday|date=2006|publisher=Cafoscarina|location=Venice|isbn=8875431051|chapter=The Sun God and the Wind Deity at Kizil|chapterurl=http://www.transoxiana.org/Eran/Articles/tianshu.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Gimbutas|first1=Marija|authorlink1=Marija Gimbutas|title=The language of the goddess: unearthing the hidden symbols of western civilization|date=1989|publisher=Harper & Row|location=San Francisco|isbn=0-06-250356-1}}</ref> Entities such as the Sun, Moon, Earth, sky, and sea were often deified.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Turner|first1=Patricia|last2=Coulter|first2=Charles Russell|title=Dictionary of ancient deities|date=2001|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=9780195145045}}</ref> [[Shrine]]s developed, which evolved into [[temple]] establishments, complete with a complex hierarchy of [[Priest|priests and priestesses]] and other functionaries. Typical of the Neolithic was a tendency to worship [[anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] [[Deity|deities]]. Among the earliest surviving written religious scriptures are the Egyptian ''[[Pyramid Texts]]'', the oldest of which date to between 2400 and 2300 BCE.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=6VBJeCoDdTUC&pg=PA1&dq=2353+-+2323+%22pyramid+texts%22|last=Allen|first=James|isbn=1-58983-182-9|title=The Ancient Egyptian Pyramid Texts |date=2007 |publisher=Scholars Press |location=Atlanta, Ga.}}</ref> Some archaeologists suggest, based on ongoing excavations of a temple complex at [[Göbekli Tepe]] ("Potbelly Hill") in southern Turkey, dating from c. 11,500 years ago, that religion predated the [[Neolithic Revolution|Agricultural Revolution]] rather than following in its wake, as had generally been assumed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Symmes|first1=Patrick|title=Turkey: Archeological Dig Reshaping Human History|url=http://europe.newsweek.com/turkey-archeological-dig-reshaping-human-history-75101|work=Newsweek|date=19 February 2010}}</ref>

