{{further information|Interwar period|Roaring Twenties|Great Depression}}
[[File:Royal Irish Rifles ration party Somme July 1916.jpg|thumb|[[World War I]] static [[trench warfare]], western Europe]]
[[File:Nagasakibomb.jpg|thumb|History's only use of [[nuclear weapon]]s in war—[[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|Hiroshima and Nagasaki]], 1945]]
The 20th century<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.20th-century.net |title=The 20th Century Research Project |publisher=20th-century.net |accessdate=18 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://econ161.berkeley.edu/TCEH/Slouch_Old.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206080625/http://econ161.berkeley.edu/TCEH/Slouch_Old.html|archivedate=6 February 2012 |title=Slouching Towards Utopia: The Economic History of the Twentieth Century |publisher=Econ161.berkeley.edu |date=1 March 2000 |accessdate=18 April 2009}}</ref> opened with [[Europe]] at an apex of wealth and power, and with much of the world under its direct [[Colonialism|colonial]] control or its indirect domination.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Etemad|first1=Bouda|title=Possessing the world: taking the measurements of colonisation from the eighteenth to the twentieth century|date=2007|publisher=Berghahn Books|location=New York|isbn=9781845453381|translator-first=Andrene |translator-last=Everson}}</ref> Much of the rest of the world was influenced by heavily Europeanized nations: the [[United States]] and [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Wells |first=H. G. |authorlink=H. G. Wells |date=1922 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FGgMAAAAIAAJ |title=The Outline of History: Being A Plain History of Life and Mankind |location=New York |publisher=The Review of Reviews |page=1200}}</ref> As the century unfolded, however, the global system dominated by rival powers was subjected to severe strains, and ultimately seemed to yield to a more fluid structure of independent nations organized on Western models.

This transformation was [[catalysis|catalysed]] by [[war]]s of unparalleled scope and devastation. [[World War I]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Herrmann|first1=David G.|title=The arming of Europe and the making of the First World War|date=1996|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=0691033749}}</ref> destroyed many of Europe's empires and monarchies, and weakened [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]] and [[France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstworldwar.com/ |title=A multimedia history of World War I |publisher=Firstworldwar.com |accessdate=18 April 2009}}</ref> In its aftermath, powerful ideologies arose. The [[Russian Revolution]]<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Bunyan |editor1-first=James |editor2-first=Harold Henry |editor2-last=Fisher |title=The Bolshevik Revolution, 1917–1918: Documents and Materials |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dTGsAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover | publisher=Stanford University Press |date=1961 |isbn=9780804703444 |orig-year=first published 1934}}</ref><ref>[[John Reed (journalist)|Reed, John]]. [http://www.marxists.org/archive/reed/1919/10days/10days/index.htm Ten Days that Shook the World]. 1919, 1st Edition, published by BONI & Liveright, Inc. for International Publishers. Transcribed and marked by David Walters for [http://www.marxists.org/archive/reed/works/index.htm John Reed Internet Archive]. Penguin Books; 1st edition. 1 June 1980. ISBN 0-14-018293-4. Retrieved 14 May 2005. {{cite web|url=http://www.marxists.org/archive/reed/1919/10days/10days/index.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-09 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516062956/http://www.marxists.org/archive/reed/1919/10days/10days/index.htm |archivedate=16 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[[Leon Trotsky|Trotsky, Leon]]. [http://www.marxists.org/archive/trotsky/works/1930-hrr/index.htm The History of the Russian Revolution]. Translated by Max Eastman, 1932. Library of Congress Catalog Card Number 8083994. ISBN 0-913460-83-4. Transcribed for the World Wide Web by John Gowland (Australia), Alphanos Pangas (Greece) and David Walters (United States). Pathfinder Press edition. 1 June 1980. ISBN 0-87348-829-6. Retrieved 14 May 2005. {{cite web|url=http://www.marxists.org/archive/trotsky/works/1930-hrr/index.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-09 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205021833/http://www.marxists.org/archive/trotsky/works/1930-hrr/index.htm |archivedate=5 December 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> of 1917 created the first [[communism|communist]] state, while the 1920s and 1930s saw [[militarism|militaristic]] [[fascism|fascist]] dictatorships gain control in [[Italy]], [[Germany]], [[Spain]] and elsewhere.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Davis |first1=W. S. |last2=Anderson |first2=W. |last3=Tyler |first3=M. W. |date=1918 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DOtGAAAAIAAJ |title=The roots of the war; a non-technical history of Europe, 1870–1914, AD |location=New York |publisher=Century}}</ref>

Ongoing national rivalries, exacerbated by the economic turmoil of the [[Great Depression]], helped precipitate [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|first=C. Peter |last=Chen |url=http://www.ww2db.com/ |title=World War II Database |publisher=Ww2db.com |accessdate=18 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/encyclopedia.do?articleId=226140 |title=World War II Encyclopedia by the History Channel |publisher=History.com |accessdate=18 April 2009}}</ref> The [[Militarism|militaristic]] [[dictatorship]]s of [[Europe]] and [[Japan]] pursued an ultimately doomed course of [[Imperialism|imperialist]] [[expansionism]]. Their defeat opened the way for the advance of [[Socialism]] and Communism into [[Central Europe]], [[Yugoslavia]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Romania]], [[Albania]], [[China]], [[North Vietnam]] and [[North Korea]].

====1945–2000====
{{Main article|20th century}}
{{further information|Cold War|Green Revolution|Space exploration|Digital Revolution}}
After [[World War II]] ended in 1945, the [[United Nations]] was founded in the hope of allaying conflicts among nations and preventing future wars.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fasulo|first1=Linda|title=An insider's guide to the UN|date=2004|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven, Conn.|isbn=0-300-10155-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Meisler|first1=Stanley|title=United Nations: the first fifty years|date=1995|publisher=The Atlantic Monthly Press|location=New York|isbn=0-87113-656-2}}</ref> The [[Soviet Union]], the [[United States]], the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Republic of China (1912–49)|China]] were recognized as the Allied "[[Four Policemen|Big Four]]" during the war and considered as the primary victors of World War II.<ref name = Justus>{{cite book |last1=Doenecke |first1=Justus D. |last2=Stoler |first2=Mark A. |title=Debating Franklin D. Roosevelt's foreign policies, 1933–1945 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xdMF9rX6mX8C&pg=PA62 |year=2005 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |accessdate=7 September 2009 |isbn=0-8476-9416-X }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|first=Walter L.|last=Hixson|title=The American Experience in World War II: American diplomacy in the Second World War|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=2003|isbn=9780415940368|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=8pRqUV1ue4IC&pg=PA204|ref=refHixson|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref> With the addition of France, these five countries became the [[Permanent members of the United Nations Security Council|permanent seats]] in the [[United Nations Security Council]]. The war had, however, left two nations, the [[United States]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Avery|first1=Samuel|title=The globalist papers|date=2004|publisher=Compari|location=Louisville, Ky.|isbn=0974197610}}</ref> and the [[Soviet Union]], with principal power to guide international affairs.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Zinn|first=Howard|title=A People's History of the United States|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9-FtlblxbLgC&printsec=frontcover|date=2003|edition=5th|place=New York|publisher=HarperPerennial Modern Classics [2005 reprint]|isbn=0-06-083865-5}}</ref> Each was suspicious of the other and feared a global spread of the other's political-economic model. This led to the [[Cold War]], a forty-five-year stand-off between the United States, the Soviet Union, and their respective allies. With the development of [[nuclear weapon]]s<ref>{{cite web|title=Race for the Super Bomb|url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/bomb/|website=American Experience|publisher=PBS}}</ref> and the subsequent [[arms race]], all of humanity were put at risk of [[Nuclear warfare|nuclear war]] between the two superpowers.<ref>As irrefutably demonstrated by a number of incidents, most prominently the October 1962 [[Cuban Missile Crisis]].</ref> Such war [[Global catastrophic risk|being viewed as impractical]], [[proxy war]]s were instead waged, at the expense of non-nuclear-armed [[Third World]] countries.

The Cold War lasted to the 1990s, when the Soviet Union's communist system began to collapse, unable to compete economically with the United States and western Europe; the Soviets' [[Central Europe]]an "[[satellite state|satellites]]" reasserted their national sovereignty, and in 1991 the Soviet Union itself [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|disintegrated]].<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Brown|editor1-first=Archie|title=The Cambridge encyclopedia of Russia and the Soviet Union|date=1984|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521231695}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Gilbert|first1=Martin|title=The Routledge atlas of Russian history|date=2006|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=0415281199|edition=3rd}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Goldman|first1=Minton F.|title=The Soviet Union and Eastern Europe|date=1986|publisher=Dushkin|location=Guilford, Conn.|isbn=9780879675615}}</ref> The United States for the time being was left as the "sole remaining superpower".<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Shultz|editor1-first=Richard H.|editor2-last=Pfaltzgraff|editor2-first=Robert L.|editor3-last=Stock|editor3-first=W. Bradley|title=Special operations forces: roles and missions in the aftermath of the cold war|date=1996|publisher=Diane Pub Co|isbn=0788171402|page=59}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Caraley|editor1-first=Demetrios James|title=American hegemony: preventive war, Iraq, and imposing democracy|date=2004|publisher=Academy of Political Science|location=New York|isbn=1884853048|page=viii}}</ref> After the 1970s, the United States' superpower status came into question as that country's economic supremacy began to show signs of slippage.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McCormick|first1=Thomas J.|title=America's half-century: United States foreign policy in the cold war and after|date=1995|publisher=The Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=0801850118|page=155}}</ref>

In the early postwar decades, the [[Africa]]n and [[Asia]]n colonies of the Belgian, British, Dutch, French and other west European empires won their formal independence.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chamberlain|first1=Muriel Evelyn|title=Decolonization : the fall of the European empires|date=1999|publisher=Blackwell|location=Oxford|isbn=9780631216025}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Abernethy|first1=David B.|title=The dynamics of global dominance : European overseas empires, 1415-1980|date=2000|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven|isbn=9780300093148}}</ref> These nations faced challenges in the form of [[neocolonialism]], poverty, illiteracy and [[Endemic (epidemiology)|endemic]] [[tropical disease]]s.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stern|first1=Nicholas|last2=Rogers|first2=F. Halsey|last3=Dethier|first3=Jean-Jacques|title=Growth and Empowerment: Making Development Happen|date=2006|publisher=MIT Press|location=Cambridge, Mass|series=Munich lectures in economics|isbn=9780262264747}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Weiss|first1=Thomas G.|title=UN voices: the struggle for development and social justice|date=2005|publisher=Indiana University Press|location=Bloomington|isbn=9780253217882|page=3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5cxA4LwpKVoC&pg=PA3|series=United Nations intellectual history project|volume=6}}</ref>

Many [[Western Europe|Western]] and [[Central Europe]]an nations gradually formed a political and economic community, the [[European Union]], which expanded eastward to include former Soviet satellites.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dinan|first1=Desmond|title=Europe recast: a history of European Union|date=2004|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=Basingstoke|isbn=978-0-333-98734-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=McCormick|first=John|authorlink=John McCormick (political scientist)|title=Understanding the European Union: a concise introduction|date=2005|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=Houndmills|isbn=978-1-4039-4451-1|edition=3rd}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Peterson|editor1-first=John|editor2-last=Shackleton|editor2-first=Michael|title=The institutions of the European Union|date=2012|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199574988|edition=3rd}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Rifkin|first1=Jeremy|title=The European dream: how Europe's vision of the future is quietly eclipsing the American dream|date=2004|publisher=Jeremy P. Tarcher|location=New York|isbn=978-1-58542-345-3}}</ref>

[[File:Apollo 17 Cernan on moon.jpg|thumb|Last [[Moon]] landing&nbsp;– [[Apollo 17]] (1972)]]
The 20th century saw explosive progress in [[science]] and [[technology]], and increased [[life expectancy]] and [[standard of living]] for much of humanity. As the developed world shifted from a [[coal]]-based to a [[petroleum]]-based economy, new transport technologies, along with the dawn of the [[Information Age]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lallana |first1=Emmanuel C. |first2=Margaret N. |last2=Uy |title=[[b:The Information Age|The Information Age]]|publisher=UNDP-APDIP|date=2003}}</ref> led to increased [[globalization]].<ref>{{cite book|editor-last1=von Braun |editor-first1=Joachim |editor-first2=Eugenio|editor-last2=Diaz-Bonilla |title=Globalization of Food and Agriculture and the Poor |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2007 |url=https://www.ifpri.org/publication/globalization-food-and-agriculture-and-poor |isbn=978-0-19-569528-1 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Friedman | first = Thomas L. | authorlink = Thomas Friedman | title = [[The World Is Flat]] | publisher = Farrar, Straus and Giroux | date = 2005 | location = New York | isbn = 0-374-29288-4 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Murray | first = Warwick E. | title = Geographies of Globalization | publisher = Routledge/Taylor and Francis | date = 2006 | location = New York | isbn = 0-415-31799-1 }}</ref> [[Space exploration]] reached throughout the [[Solar System]]. The structure of [[DNA]], the template of [[life]], was discovered,<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Clayton|editor1-first=Julie|editor2-last=Dennis|editor2-first=Carina|title=50 years of DNA|date=2003|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=New York|isbn=978-1-4039-1479-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Watson|first1=James D.|author1-link=James Watson |editor1-last=Stent|editor1-first=Gunther S.|title-link=The Double Helix|title=The Double Helix: A Personal Account of the Discovery of the Structure of DNA|date=1980|publisher=W. W. Norton|location=New York|isbn=978-0-393-95075-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Calladine|first1=Chris R.|last2=Drew|first2=Horace R.|last3=Luisi|first3=Ben F.|last4=Travers|first4=Andrew A.|title=Understanding DNA the molecule & how it works|date=2008|publisher=Elsevier Academic Press|location=Amsterdam|isbn=978-0-12-155089-9}}</ref> and the [[human genome]] was sequenced, a major milestone in the understanding of [[human biology]] and the treatment of [[disease]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genome.gov/ |title=The National Human Genome Research Institute |publisher=Genome.gov |accessdate=18 April 2009}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ensembl.org/ Ensembl] The [[Ensembl]] Genome Browser Project</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=mapview |url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mapview/map_search.cgi?taxid=9606 |title=National Library of Medicine human genome viewer |publisher=Ncbi.nlm.nih.gov |date=26 March 2008 |accessdate=18 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ucsc.edu/ |title=UCSC Genome Browser |publisher=Genome.ucsc.edu |accessdate=18 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ornl.gov/sci/techresources/Human_Genome/project/info.shtml |title=Human Genome Project |publisher=Ornl.gov |date=26 March 2008 |accessdate=18 April 2009}}</ref> Global [[literacy]] rates continued to rise, and the percentage of the world's [[Labour economics|labour]] pool needed to produce [[humankind]]'s [[food]] supply continued to drop.

The technologies of sound recordings, motion pictures, and radio and television broadcasting produced a means for rapid dissemination of information and entertainment. In the last decade of the twentieth century, a rapid increase took place in the use of computers, including [[personal computer]]s. A global communication network emerged in the [[Internet]].

The century saw several global threats emerge or become more serious or more widely recognized, including [[nuclear proliferation]], [[global climate change]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mun|first1=Yuri|title=Earth Radiation Budget|url=http://marine.rutgers.edu/cool/education/class/yuri/erb.html|website=marine.rutgers.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Wood |first=R.W. |date=1909 |title=Note on the Theory of the Greenhouse| journal=Philosophical Magazine| volume=17| pages=319–320| url=http://www.wmconnolley.org.uk/sci/wood_rw.1909.html | doi=10.1080/14786440208636602}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.vox.com/2015/12/12/9894234/climate-change-explained |title = Why climate change is so important, in one chart |first1=Joss |last1=Fong |first2=Estelle |last2=Caswell |publisher =Vox.com |date = April 22, 2016 |accessdate = 28 April 2016}}</ref> [[deforestation]], [[Human overpopulation|overpopulation]], deadly [[epidemic]]s of diseases such as [[Ebola virus]], [[Near-Earth object|near-Earth asteroids and comets]],<ref name = "BROWN02">{{cite news|url =https://www.sciencenews.org/archive/call-catastrophes?mode=magazine&context=4378&tgt=nr|title = The Call of Catastrophes|first = Richard | last = Monastersky|work = Science News Online|date = 1 March 1997|subscription=y|accessdate = 23 October 2007}}</ref> [[supervolcano]] eruptions, and the dwindling of global [[natural resource]]s (particularly [[fossil fuel]]s).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Edwards|first1=Andres R.|title=The sustainability revolution: portrait of a paradigm shift|date=2005|publisher=New Society Publishers|location=Gabriola, B.C.|isbn=1550923250|page=52}}</ref>

===Contemporary history===
{{Main article|Contemporary history}}

====21st century====
[[File:Internet map 1024.jpg|thumb|Depiction of the [[Internet]], a source of [[information]] and [[communication]]]]
{{Main article|21st century}}
A man-made hazard to world survival that dominated concerns in the second half of the 20th century, continues into the 21st.  Countries ambitious to develop and deploy [[nuclear weapons]] are discouraged from doing so by countries that already possess them.  At the same time, nuclear-armed countries have shown little urgency about honoring their 20th-century pledge to eventually eliminate all nuclear weapons.  Such weapons continue to be equally hazardous to their owners as to their potential targets.<ref>[[Eric Schlosser]], ''[[Command and Control: Nuclear Weapons, the Damascus Accident, and the Illusion of Safety]]'', [[Penguin Press]], 2013, ISBN 1594202273.</ref> 

The 21st century has been marked by growing [[economic globalization]] and integration, with consequent increased risk to interlinked economies, and by the expansion of communications with [[mobile phone]]s and the [[Internet]].  The rise of the [[personal computer]] and the the [[Worldwide Web]] has caused fundamental changes in multiple aspects of human society, in both business and personal spheres.

The early 21st century saw escalating intra- and international strife in the [[Middle East]] and [[Afghanistan]], stimulated by vast economic disparities, by dissatisfaction with governments dominated by Western interests, by inter-ethnic and inter-sectarian feuds, and by the longest war in the history of the [[United States]], the proximate cause for which was [[Osama bin Laden]]'s provocative 2001 destruction of [[New York City]]'s [[World Trade Center (1973–2001)|World Trade Center]].  

U.S. military involvements in the Middle East and Afghanistan drained U.S. economic resources at a time when the U.S. and other Western countries were experiencing mounting socioeconomic dislocations aggravated by the [[robotization]] of work and the exportation of industries to cheaper-workforce countries.
 
Worldwide [[demand]] and [[competition]] for [[Natural resource|resources]] has risen due to growing populations and industrialization, especially in India, China and [[Brazil]] (see [[List of countries by carbon dioxide emissions per capita]]). This increased demand is causing increased levels of environmental degradation and a growing threat of [[global warming]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Energy and power: a Scientific American book|date=1971|publisher=W H Freeman|location=San Francisco|isbn=9780716709398|pages=vii–viii|chapter=Foreword}}</ref> That, and a need for reliable energy supplies independent of politically volatile regions, has spurred the development of alternate, [[renewable energy|renewable]] sources of [[energy]] (notably [[solar energy]] and [[Wind power|wind energy]]), proposals for cleaner [[fossil fuel|fossil-fuel]] technologies<ref>Critiqued in {{cite journal |first=David |last=Biello |title=The Carbon Capture Fallacy |journal=Scientific American |volume=314 |issue=1 |date=January 2016 |pages=58–65|pmid=26887197 |doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0116-58}}.</ref> and for expanded use of [[Nuclear power|nuclear energy]] (somewhat dampened by [[Nuclear accidents#Nuclear power plant accidents|nuclear-plant accidents]]),<ref>{{cite book |first=M. King |last=Hubbert |authorlink=M. King Hubbert |chapter=The Energy Resources of the Earth |title=Energy and power: a Scientific American book|date=1971|publisher=W H Freeman|location=San Francisco|isbn=9780716709398|pages=31–40}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Global Trends In Sustainable Energy Investment 2008| url=http://sefi.unep.org/english/globaltrends |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221140323/http://sefi.unep.org/english/globaltrends|archive-date=21 December 2008| website=Sustainable Energy Finance Initiative|publisher=[[United Nations Environment Programme|UNEP]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Home Page|url=http://www.nrel.gov/|website=National Renewable Energy Laboratory}}</ref> and, conversely, calls to eschew the indiscriminate large-scale employment of the "fissile-fossil complex" of fissile- (nuclear) and fossil-fuel (coal, petroleum, natural-gas) energy generation.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Christopher |last=Kasparek |title=A Futurological Note: [[Bolesław Prus|Prus]] on [[H. G. Wells]] and the Year 2000 |journal=[[The Polish Review]] |volume=XLVIII |issue=1 |date=2003 |pages=98–99|jstor=25779372}}</ref>

